<paper>
Paper Title: Using Reachable Sets for Trajectory Planning of Automated Vehicles
Paper Abstract: The computational effort of trajectory planning for automated vehicles often increases with the complexity of the traffic situation. This is particularly problematic in safety-critical situations, in which the vehicle must react in a timely manner. We present a novel motion planning approach for automated vehicles, which combines set-based reachability analysis with convex optimization to address this issue. This combination makes it possible to find driving maneuvers even in small and convoluted solution spaces. In contrast to existing work, the computation time of our approach typically decreases, the more complex situations become. We demonstrate the benefits of our motion planner in scenarios from the CommonRoad benchmark suite and validate the approach on a real test vehicle.
</paper>

<paper_classification>
"contribution" = proposes something new (method, technique, dataset, framework, benchmark, etc.)
"survey" = literature review, overview, meta-analysis, position papers (only references existing work)
</paper_classification>

<entity_types>
task      - Problem being solved (image classification, theorem proving, protein folding)
method    - Technique, algorithm, procedure (gradient descent, CRISPR, induction)
data      - Datasets, databases, benchmarks (ImageNet, MNIST, arXiv corpus)
artifact  - Pre-built: trained models, proof libraries (GPT-4, Mathlib, Cas9)
tool      - Software, instruments, platforms (PyTorch, Lean prover, microscope)
concept   - Abstract ideas, theories, frameworks (attention, category theory)
other     - Entities that don't fit above categories
</entity_types>

<relations>
uses     - Anything EXISTING that the paper uses (methods, datasets, tools, concepts, tasks)
proposes - Anything NEW/NOVEL that the paper creates or introduces

VALIDATION REQUIREMENTS:
- ALL papers MUST have at least 1 "uses" (papers always build on existing work)
- CONTRIBUTION papers MUST have at least 1 "proposes" (they must create something new)
</relations>

<output_json>
{
  "paper_type": "contribution" or "survey",
  "triples": [
    {
      "name": "Wikipedia Article Title",
      "relation": "uses|proposes",
      "entity_type": "task|method|data|artifact|tool|concept|other",
      "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/...",
      "relevance": "Why this matters (1 sentence)"
    }
  ]
}
</output_json>

<YOUR_TODO_LIST>
FIRST, add ALL of these to your todo list with "TodoWrite" tool:

CRITICAL: Todo content must be copied exactly as is written here, with NO CHANGES. These todos are intentionally detailed so that another LLM could read each one without any external context and understand exactly what it has to do.

1. Read ./triples_output.json. Classify paper as "contribution" or "survey". Edit triples_output.json to set paper_type field.

2. List ALL triples EXPLICITLY mentioned in title/abstract. For each, determine entity_type and relation.

3. For each triple: Use WebSearch tool with allowed_domains=["en.wikipedia.org"] to search "[entity name]" to find the correct Wikipedia article. IMPORTANT: Always include allowed_domains parameter to restrict to English Wikipedia.

4. Edit triples_output.json to add all triples. For each triple:
   - name: Use the Wikipedia article title (e.g., "Gradient descent" not "gradient descent algorithm")

5. Run validation: python validate_triple_json.py

6. If validation errors: Fix the errors (use WebSearch with allowed_domains=["en.wikipedia.org"] again if needed for incorrect URLs), edit triples_output.json, and rerun validation. MUST REPEAT until validation passes.

This ensures only English Wikipedia results are returned. Do NOT search without allowed_domains.

## Definition

Convex optimization is a subfield of mathematical optimization that studies the problem of minimizing convex functions over convex sets (or, equivalently, maximizing concave functions over convex sets).

## Key Properties

One of the most important advantages of convex optimization is its computational tractability. Many classes of convex optimization problems admit polynomial-time algorithms. Additionally, every point that is local minimum is also a global minimum in convex optimization problems, which eliminates the challenge of distinguishing between local and global optima.

## Solution Methods

Convex optimization problems are solved using various algorithms depending on their structure:

- For unconstrained (or equality-constrained) problems with a general convex objective that is twice-differentiable, Newton's method can be used, reducing a general unconstrained convex problem to a sequence of quadratic problems.
- Other efficient algorithms for unconstrained minimization are gradient descent (a special case of steepest descent).
- For problems with inequality constraints, a common way to solve them is to reduce them to unconstrained problems by adding a barrier function, enforcing the inequality constraints, to the objective function. Such methods are called interior point methods.

## Applications

Convex optimization can be used to model problems in the following fields: Portfolio optimization, Worst-case risk analysis, Optimal advertising, Variations of statistical regression (including regularization and quantile regression), Model fitting (particularly multiclass classification), Electricity generation optimization, and Combinatorial optimization.

## Software Ecosystem

There is a large software ecosystem for convex optimization with two main categories: solvers on the one hand and modeling tools (or interfaces) on the other hand.(no content)Examples include modelling tools such as CVXPY and JuMP.jl and solvers such as SCS and MOSEK.

## What is Motion Planning?

Motion planning, also known as path planning (or the navigation problem or the piano mover's problem), is a computational problem to find a sequence of valid configurations that moves the object from the source to destination.

## Core Problem

A basic motion planning problem is to compute a continuous path that connects a start configuration S and a goal configuration G, while avoiding collision with known obstacles.

## Applications

Motion planning has several robotics applications, such as autonomy, automation, and robot design in CAD software, as well as applications in other fields, such as animating digital characters, video game, architectural design, robotic surgery, and the study of biological molecules.

## Key Algorithms

Sampling-based algorithms are currently considered state-of-the-art for motion planning in high-dimensional spaces, and have been applied to problems which have dozens or even hundreds of dimensions (robotic manipulators, biological molecules, animated digital characters, and legged robots).

## Approaches

The search results describe several motion planning approaches:

- **Grid-based approaches**: These overlay a grid on configuration space and assume each configuration is identified with a grid point. At each grid point, the robot is allowed to move to adjacent grid points as long as the line between them is completely contained within free space. Search algorithms like A* are used to find a path from the start to the goal.

- **Sampling-based algorithms**: These represent the configuration space with a roadmap of sampled configurations. A basic algorithm samples N configurations and retains those in free space to use as milestones, then constructs a roadmap that connects two milestones if the line segment between them is completely in free space.

- **Real-time path planning**: Real-time path planning consists of motion planning methods that can adapt to real time changes in the environment, ranging from primitive algorithms that stop a robot when it approaches an obstacle to more complex algorithms that continuously take in information from the surroundings and create a plan to avoid obstacles.

The Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE) classifies road vehicle autonomy in six levels: Level 1 is driver assistance where the vehicle controls steering or speed autonomously in specific circumstances; Level 2 is partial automation where the vehicle controls both steering and speed autonomously; Level 3 is conditional automation where the vehicle operates under normal conditions but requires driver readiness; Level 4 is high automation where the vehicle travels autonomously without driver oversight under normal conditions; and Level 5 is full autonomy where the vehicle can complete travel autonomously in any environmental conditions.
